        "content": "{\n  \"name\": \"coderegon-trail\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Learn codebases through play - Coderegon Trail games, TTS-narrated code walkthroughs, and comprehension quizzes\",\n  \"author\": {\n    \"name\": \"Flow Club\"\n  },\n  \"keywords\": [\n    \"diff\",\n    \"review\",\n    \"tts\",\n    \"walkthrough\",\n    \"pair-programming\",\n    \"narration\"\n  ]\n}",
        "language": "json"
      },
      "narration": "Welcome to the Coderegon Trail plugin. This PR builds an entire Claude Code plugin from scratch. It teaches web framework concepts through a retro Oregon Trail-style game. The whole thing is markdown specs and shell scripts. No build step, no dependencies. Twenty commits and forty-three files create a complete game engine, TTS narration system, and seven framework trails."
    },
    {
      "name": "Command Summit",
      "subtitle": "The Game Launcher",
      "concept": "How the fly-visual command orchestrates game generation",
      "landmarkType": "mountain",
      "code": {
        "file": "commands/fly-visual.md",
        "startLine": 1,
        "endLine": 18,
        "content": "---\ndescription: \"Launch a Coderegon Trail game to learn a web framework's request pipeline — or review a PR\"\nargument-hint: \"[next | rails | django | express | react | laravel | openclaw | PR# | PR-URL | git-range]\"\nallowed-tools:\n  - Bash(git:*)\n  - Bash(gh:*)\n  - Bash(say:*)\n  - Bash(afplay:*)\n  - Bash(curl:*)\n  - Bash(${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/*:*)\n  - Read\n  - Grep\n  - Glob\n  - Task\n  - Skill\n  - Write\nmodel: opus\n---",
        "language": "yaml"
      },
      "narration": "This is the heart of the plugin. The fly-visual command is the main entry point. Notice the YAML frontmatter: it declares allowed tools, the model to use, and a description. This one file defines how Claude detects whether you want a framework trail or a PR review. It supports seven frameworks by name, plus PR numbers, URLs, and git ranges."
    },
    {
      "name": "Game Engine Pass",
      "subtitle": "State Machine and Scoring",
      "concept": "How the game state machine drives the player experience",
      "landmarkType": "mountain",
      "code": {
        "file": "skills/visualization/SKILL.md",
        "startLine": 127,
        "endLine": 155,
        "content": "## Game State Machine\n\nThe game progresses through these states:\n\n| State | Description | Transitions To |\n|-------|------------|----------------|\n| TITLE | Title screen with pixel art logo | SETUP |\n| SETUP | Pick framework (if not pre-selected), name party | TRAVEL |\n| TRAVEL | Wagon moving between stops, scrolling landscape | STOP, EVENT |\n| STOP | At a trail stop — show code, narration | TRAVEL, EVENT |\n| EVENT | Quiz/decision event — weather, river, encounter | TRAVEL, DEATH |\n| RIVER | Special river crossing event (major boundary) | TRAVEL, DEATH |\n| DEATH | Game over — tombstone with death message | TITLE |\n| WIN | Arrived at Response Frontier — score card | TITLE |\n\n## Scoring\n\n| Action | Points |\n|--------|--------|\n| Correct answer | +10 health, +1 morale streak |\n| Partial answer | +5 health |\n| Wrong answer | -15 health, reset morale streak, party member takes damage |\n| Hint used | -1 supply |\n| Streak bonus (3+) | +5 bonus per correct in streak |\n| Party member death | Permanent — cannot answer questions about that concept |",
        "language": "markdown"
      },
      "narration": "The game runs on an eight-state machine. Title, setup, travel, stop, event, river, death, and win. Each state transitions to the next in a specific order. Wrong answers cost fifteen health and damage the party member tied to that concept. Get three right in a row and you earn streak bonuses. If a party member dies, that concept is locked out for good."
    },
    {
      "name": "Trail Data Canyon",
      "subtitle": "Seven Frameworks, Fifteen Events Each",
      "concept": "How framework-trails.md encodes learning content as game data",
      "landmarkType": "desert",
      "code": {
        "file": "skills/visualization/references/framework-trails.md",
        "startLine": 1,
        "endLine": 18,
        "content": "# Framework Trails — Trail Data Reference\n\nTrail definitions for each supported framework. Each trail maps the framework's request/render pipeline to ~8 stops on the Coderegon Trail.\n\n---\n\n## Next.js — \"The App Router Trail\"\n\n### Trail Overview\nFollow a request from the browser through Next.js App Router's middleware, file-based routing, layout nesting, server/client component boundary, data fetching, and final response rendering.\n\n### Stops\n\n#### Stop 0: Independence, MO — The Entry Point\n- **concept**: Project initialization\n- **landmarkType**: town\n- **code**:",
        "language": "markdown"
      },
      "narration": "This is where the learning content lives. Framework-trails dot M-D is over three thousand lines. It defines seven complete trails: Next.js, Rails, Django, Express, React, Laravel, and OpenClaw. Each trail maps a framework's request pipeline to about eight stops. Every stop has a code snippet, narration, and concept tag. Each framework also has fifteen quiz events across three difficulty tiers."
    },
    {
      "name": "TTS River Crossing",
      "subtitle": "Text-to-Speech Engine",
      "concept": "How the TTS system narrates the experience",
      "landmarkType": "river",
      "code": {
        "file": "scripts/tts.sh",
        "startLine": 1,
        "endLine": 19,
        "content": "#!/bin/bash\n# scripts/tts.sh - Universal TTS wrapper for diff-pair-review\n# Supports macOS say (default) and OpenAI TTS API with automatic fallback\nset -euo pipefail\n\nSCRIPT_DIR=\"$(cd \"$(dirname \"${BASH_SOURCE[0]}\")\" && pwd)\"\nPLUGIN_ROOT=\"$(dirname \"$SCRIPT_DIR\")\"\n\nsource \"${SCRIPT_DIR}/lib/utils.sh\"\nsource \"${SCRIPT_DIR}/lib/config.sh\"\n\n# Defaults (overridden by config/env/flags)\nENGINE=\"${DIFF_REVIEW_TTS_ENGINE:-say}\"\nVOICE=\"${DIFF_REVIEW_TTS_VOICE:-}\"\nRATE=\"${DIFF_REVIEW_TTS_RATE:-200}\"\nSPEED=\"${DIFF_REVIEW_TTS_SPEED:-1.0}\"\nMODEL=\"${DIFF_REVIEW_TTS_MODEL:-tts-1}\"\nDEBUG=\"${DIFF_REVIEW_DEBUG:-false}\"\nTEMP_DIR=\"${TMPDIR:-/tmp}/diff-review-tts\"",
        "language": "bash"
      },
      "narration": "Here's a key boundary crossing. The TTS script bridges Claude's text output to spoken audio. It supports two engines: macOS say as the default, and OpenAI's TTS API as a premium option. Config priority flows from CLI flags, to environment variables, to the JSON config file, to built-in defaults. If OpenAI fails, it falls back to say automatically. The script runs audio asynchronously so it never blocks the review."
    },
    {
      "name": "Pixel Art Plateau",
      "subtitle": "Canvas Rendering and Visual Style",
      "concept": "How the game renders retro pixel art without any image assets",
      "landmarkType": "forest",
      "code": {
        "file": "skills/visualization/references/pixel-art-style.md",
        "startLine": 49,
        "endLine": 75,
        "content": "### Landscape Region (Canvas)\n\n- **Sky layer** (top 40%): Gradient sky with optional clouds, sun/moon\n- **Mountain layer** (20-40%): Parallax mountains, scroll at 0.3x speed\n- **Tree layer** (40-60%): Parallax trees/features, scroll at 0.6x speed\n- **Ground layer** (bottom 30%): Trail path, grass, rocks, scroll at 1x speed\n- **Wagon** (centered on trail): Animated wheels, framework logo as flag\n\n#### Parallax Scrolling\n- 3 layers scroll at different speeds for depth effect\n- Mountains: 0.3x wagon speed\n- Trees/features: 0.6x wagon speed\n- Ground: 1.0x wagon speed\n- Creates convincing depth with minimal rendering cost\n\n#### Landmark Types\nEach stop has a landmark rendered on the landscape:\n\n| Type | Visual |\n|------|--------|\n| town | Cluster of pixel buildings, signpost with stop name |\n| mountain | Prominent peak with snow cap |\n| river | Animated blue water band across the trail |\n| forest | Dense tree cluster |\n| desert | Sandy ground, cacti, minimal trees |\n| camp | Campfire, tent, small clearing |",
        "language": "markdown"
      },
      "narration": "Every game is two to three thousand lines of self-contained HTML. No image assets at all. The landscape is drawn procedurally on Canvas with three parallax layers. Mountains scroll at point three speed, trees at point six, ground at full speed. The wagon has animated wheels and a colored flag. All of it rendered programmatically at sixty frames per second."
    },
    {
      "name": "Agent Outpost",
      "subtitle": "Sonnet-Powered Analysis Agents",
      "concept": "How agents extract trail data from real codebases and PRs",
      "landmarkType": "camp",
      "code": {
        "file": "agents/pr-trail-extractor.md",
        "startLine": 1,
        "endLine": 15,
        "content": "---\ndescription: Analyzes a pull request or git range and extracts trail data for the Coderegon Trail game\ntools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash(git:*), Bash(gh:*)\nmodel: sonnet\n---\n\n# PR Trail Data Extractor Agent\n\nYou analyze a pull request or git range and produce structured trail data for the Coderegon Trail game. The trail maps the PR's change groups to ~5-8 stops, with code snippets, narration, and quiz events at each stop.\n\n## Your Task\n\nGiven a PR source (number, URL, or git range), produce a JSON trail data object that the Coderegon Trail game can consume.",
        "language": "yaml"
      },
      "narration": "The plugin uses five agents, all running on Sonnet. This PR trail extractor is the one analyzing us right now. It reads diffs, groups changes by feature, ranks them by importance, and produces the JSON trail data that the game consumes. There's also a trail-data-extractor for repos, a diff-narrator and codebase-narrator for walkthroughs, and a quiz-generator for comprehension checks."
    },
    {
      "name": "Merge Frontier Approach",
      "subtitle": "Narration Skill and Shared Infrastructure",
      "concept": "How all the pieces connect into a coherent plugin",
      "landmarkType": "town",
      "code": {
        "file": "skills/narration/SKILL.md",
        "startLine": 1,
        "endLine": 24,
        "content": "---\nname: Narration\ndescription: This skill should be used when generating spoken explanations of code, diffs, or architecture. Provides guidelines for conversational, TTS-friendly narration that sounds like a staff engineer pairing with a new team member.\nversion: 1.0.0\n---\n\n# Narration Skill\n\nGenerate spoken narration for code walkthroughs and diff reviews. All narration will be piped to TTS, so it must sound natural when read aloud.\n\n## Core Principles\n\n1. **Conversational** — Talk like a helpful colleague, not a textbook. Use \"Let's look at...\", \"Notice how...\", \"The reason for this is...\"\n2. **Educational** — Explain WHY changes were made or WHY code is structured a way, not just WHAT the code does\n3. **Progressive** — Start high-level, let the user drill into detail on demand\n4. **Engaging** — Vary pacing, use transitions (\"Now the interesting part is...\"), highlight non-obvious decisions",
        "language": "yaml"
      },
      "narration": "The narration skill ties everything together. It governs how Claude speaks about code. Conversational, not robotic. Explain why, not what. Sentences under twenty-five words for natural speech. Say slash for paths. Never read code syntax literally. This single spec ensures that whether you're playing the trail game, reviewing a diff, or walking through a codebase, the voice stays consistent and human."
    }
  ],
  "events": [
    {
      "type": "encounter",
      "trigger": "after_stop",
      "triggerStop": 1,
      "title": "A Fellow Traveler Asks About Plugin Architecture",
      "text": "You meet a developer on the trail who asks: 'I see this plugin has commands, agents, and skills. What's the difference?'",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Commands are user-facing CLI entry points, agents are Sonnet-powered analysis workers, and skills are reusable generation guidelines",
          "correct": true,
          "explanation": "Exactly right. Commands in the commands folder define what the user types. Agents in the agents folder run on Sonnet to analyze code and produce structured data. Skills in the skills folder provide guidelines for how to generate output like HTML games or TTS narration."
        },
        {
          "text": "They're all the same thing — just markdown files with different names",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "While they are all markdown files, they serve different roles. Commands use model opus and are user-facing. Agents use model sonnet and are spawned as sub-tasks. Skills provide generation guidelines without running independently."
        },
        {
          "text": "Commands run shell scripts, agents call APIs, and skills handle the UI",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "Not quite. Commands are markdown specs that Claude follows. Agents are also markdown specs but for sub-tasks running on Sonnet. Shell scripts live in the scripts folder and are called by any of them. Skills define guidelines, not UI directly."
        }
      ],
      "concept": "Command Architecture",
      "difficulty": "easy"
    },
    {
      "type": "weather",
      "trigger": "after_stop",
      "triggerStop": 2,
      "title": "State Machine Storm!",
      "text": "A storm rolls in! Your game is stuck between states. In the Coderegon Trail state machine, what happens when a player answers a quiz event incorrectly and their health drops to zero?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "The game transitions from EVENT to DEATH state, showing a tombstone with a randomly selected death message",
          "correct": true,
          "explanation": "Correct. The EVENT state can transition to either TRAVEL (on survival) or DEATH. At zero health, the death sequence triggers: screen fades, a pixel tombstone rises, and a death message typewriter-animates onto the screen."
        },
        {
          "text": "The game pauses and asks if you want to continue with reduced health",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "There's no continue-on-death mechanic. When health hits zero, the game transitions to the DEATH state. The only option is to restart from the TITLE screen."
        },
        {
          "text": "The party member dies but the game continues to the next stop",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "Party member damage and player death are separate. A wrong answer damages the related party member by one HP and costs fifteen health. But if total health reaches zero, it's game over regardless of party status."
        }
      ],
      "concept": "Game Engine",
      "difficulty": "easy"
