        },
        {
          "text": "The game uses adaptive difficulty — it starts easy and increases based on your score",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "There's no adaptive system. Difficulty is set at game start when you pick your profession. Each profession maps to specific tier combinations. The game filters events by those tiers and shows all matching events."
        }
      ],
      "concept": "Trail Data",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "type": "misfortune",
      "trigger": "after_stop",
      "triggerStop": 4,
      "title": "TTS Engine Failure!",
      "text": "Your TTS engine has broken down on the trail! The tts.sh script supports two engines. What is the configuration priority order, and what happens when the OpenAI engine fails?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Priority is CLI flags, then env vars, then config/tts.json, then defaults — and OpenAI auto-falls back to macOS say on failure",
          "correct": true,
          "explanation": "Exactly. The config loader in lib slash config dot sh checks each layer. CLI flags override environment variables, which override the JSON config file, which override hardcoded defaults. If OpenAI returns an error, the script warns and calls exec_say_tts as a fallback."
        },
        {
          "text": "The JSON config file has highest priority, and OpenAI failure crashes the script",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "The config file is actually third in priority, behind CLI flags and environment variables. And the script handles OpenAI failures gracefully with an automatic fallback to the macOS say command."
        },
        {
          "text": "Environment variables override everything, and OpenAI failure retries three times before giving up",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "CLI flags actually take the highest priority. And there's no retry logic — on OpenAI failure, the script immediately falls back to macOS say. The fallback is a single clean switch, not a retry loop."
        }
      ],
      "concept": "Shell Infrastructure",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "type": "encounter",
      "trigger": "after_stop",
      "triggerStop": 5,
      "title": "A Pixel Artist Shares Wisdom",
      "text": "You meet a pixel artist who asks: 'How does a two thousand line HTML file create convincing landscape depth with no image assets?'",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Three-layer parallax scrolling on Canvas — mountains at 0.3x speed, trees at 0.6x, ground at 1.0x — all drawn procedurally with basic shapes",
          "correct": true,
          "explanation": "Right. The pixel art style guide specifies three parallax layers at different scroll speeds. Mountains are triangles with snow caps, trees are triangle-on-rectangle pines, and the ground is a trail strip. Everything is Canvas drawing calls — no images loaded."
        },
        {
          "text": "It uses CSS transforms and layered divs to create a parallax effect with DOM elements",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "The landscape rendering uses HTML5 Canvas, not DOM elements. The style guide specifies a Canvas plus DOM hybrid where Canvas handles the landscape and DOM handles text UI. The parallax is in the Canvas drawing loop, not CSS transforms."
        },
        {
          "text": "It embeds base64-encoded pixel art images that scroll at different rates",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "A core principle of the visualization skill is 'no external dependencies.' All pixel art is drawn programmatically on Canvas. The wagon, trees, mountains, and rivers are all function calls that draw basic shapes — no image data at all."
        }
      ],
      "concept": "Game Engine",
      "difficulty": "medium"
    },
    {
      "type": "weather",
      "trigger": "after_stop",
      "triggerStop": 6,
      "title": "Agent Coordination Blizzard!",
      "text": "A blizzard hits! Your agents are lost. The plugin uses five different agents. Why do commands run on Opus while agents run on Sonnet?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "text": "Commands are user-facing orchestrators that need Opus-level reasoning for complex multi-step flows, while agents do focused extraction tasks where Sonnet is fast and cost-effective",
          "correct": true,
          "explanation": "Exactly. Commands like fly-visual coordinate multiple steps: parsing input, spawning agents, generating HTML, and opening browsers. That orchestration needs strong reasoning. Agents like trail-data-extractor or quiz-generator do one focused task — analyze a diff, generate questions — where Sonnet's speed and lower cost make more sense."
        },
        {
          "text": "It's arbitrary — they could all run on the same model without any difference",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "The model choice is deliberate. Commands need complex multi-step reasoning: parsing ambiguous user input, deciding between framework and PR mode, orchestrating agents, and generating HTML. Agents do focused extraction. The YAML frontmatter explicitly declares which model each uses."
        },
        {
          "text": "Opus handles the audio processing for TTS while Sonnet handles the text generation",
          "correct": false,
          "explanation": "TTS is handled by shell scripts, not by the AI models. The Opus versus Sonnet split is about reasoning complexity. Commands orchestrate complex flows with many decisions. Agents perform focused analysis tasks. The model choice reflects the complexity of each role."
        }
      ],
      "concept": "Command Architecture",
      "difficulty": "hard"
    },
    {
      "type": "misfortune",
      "trigger": "after_stop",
      "triggerStop": 7,
      "title": "Narration Guidelines Gone Wrong!",
